<Layout title="Section 10 – Specimen Collection">
  <h1>Section 10: Specimen Collection</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.10 – Collects Specimens</em></p>
  <p>
    Understand the steps of blood, wound, sputum, and urinary specimen collection. Recognize
    abnormal lab values and implement them into an SBAR plan of care.
  </p>

  <h2 id="specimen-collection">Principles of Specimen Collection</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Use the correct collection container and label at the bedside (two patient identifiers).</li>
    <li>Collect specimens at the correct time (e.g., fasting glucose, timed urine).</li>
    <li>Use aseptic technique to avoid contaminating specimens.</li>
    <li>Transport specimens to the lab promptly; follow facility policy for temperature-sensitive specimens.</li>
    <li>Document collection time, site, and any pertinent patient conditions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="urinary-specimens">Urinary Specimens</h2>
  <h3>Midstream Clean-Catch Urine</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Instruct patient to clean perineum front to back with antiseptic wipes.</li>
    <li>Begin voiding into toilet; after stream is established, collect mid-portion of stream into sterile container.</li>
    <li>Refrigerate if not transported within 30 minutes.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>From an Indwelling Catheter</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Clamp catheter 15–30 minutes to allow urine accumulation.</li>
    <li>Clean sampling port with alcohol; aspirate using sterile syringe.</li>
    <li>Never disconnect catheter tubing or collect from drainage bag.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Urine Dipstick (Chemical Screening)</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Normal</th><th>Abnormal Significance</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>pH</td><td>4.5–8.0</td><td>Alkaline urine may indicate UTI or renal tubular acidosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Specific gravity</td><td>1.005–1.030</td><td>Low = dilute (overhydration); High = concentrated (dehydration)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Protein</td><td>Negative</td><td>Positive = kidney disease, preeclampsia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Glucose</td><td>Negative</td><td>Positive = diabetes, renal threshold exceeded</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Blood/RBCs</td><td>Negative</td><td>Positive = UTI, kidney stones, trauma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Nitrites / Leukocyte esterase</td><td>Negative</td><td>Positive = bacterial infection (UTI)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ketones</td><td>Negative</td><td>Positive = DKA, prolonged fasting, starvation</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="blood-glucose">Blood Glucose Testing</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Obtain capillary blood from fingertip (lateral aspect preferred — less painful).</li>
    <li>Warm the finger to improve blood flow; wipe away first drop; use second drop for testing.</li>
    <li>Normal fasting glucose: 70–99 mg/dL; document result and notify provider of critical values.</li>
    <li>Critical low: &lt; 50–60 mg/dL; Critical high: &gt; 400–500 mg/dL (per facility policy).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="stool-specimens">Stool Specimens</h2>
  <h3>Fecal Occult Blood Test (FOBT)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Detects hidden blood in stool — screens for GI bleeding, colorectal cancer.</li>
    <li>Patient teaching: avoid red meat, vitamin C, aspirin, and NSAIDs 3 days before test (guaiac method).</li>
    <li>Collect small stool sample from two different areas of stool; apply to card.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Gastric Occult Blood Testing</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Obtained from NG tube aspirate; tests for upper GI bleeding.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="sputum">Sputum Specimen</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Instruct patient to take deep breaths and cough forcefully to raise secretions from lower airways.</li>
    <li>Collect in early morning when secretions are most concentrated.</li>
    <li>Collect 3–5 mL of sputum (not saliva) in sterile container.</li>
    <li>Wear gloves and mask; transport to lab immediately.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="wound-culture">Wound Culture</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Irrigate wound with normal saline before culturing to remove surface contaminants.</li>
    <li>Use sterile swab to collect from the base of the wound, not the surface exudate.</li>
    <li>Rotate swab over 1 cm² area using moderate pressure (Levine technique).</li>
    <li>Transport in culture medium immediately.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="sbar-labs">SBAR for Abnormal Lab Values</h2>
  <p>
    When abnormal lab results are identified, communicate findings to the provider using
    the SBAR format and document the communication.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>SBAR Component</th><th>Example Content</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Situation</strong></td><td>"Mr. Jones in Room 204 has a blood glucose of 48 mg/dL."</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Background</strong></td><td>"He is a Type 2 diabetic on metformin and insulin. He received his morning insulin but skipped breakfast."</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Assessment</strong></td><td>"He is diaphoretic, confused, and shaking. I believe he is hypoglycemic."</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Recommendation</strong></td><td>"I would like an order for 15–20 g of fast-acting carbohydrate orally or IV dextrose."</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Clinical Skills</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Collecting a Midstream Urine Specimen</li>
    <li>Fecal Occult Blood Testing</li>
    <li>Performing Gastric Occult Blood Testing</li>
    <li>Collecting a Sputum Specimen</li>
    <li>Collecting a Specimen for Wound Culture</li>
    <li>Performing Blood Glucose Testing</li>
    <li>Screening Urine for Chemical Properties</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="key-terms">Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>FOBT:</strong> Fecal occult blood test — detects hidden blood in stool.</li>
    <li><strong>Specific gravity:</strong> Measure of urine concentration relative to water (normal 1.005–1.030).</li>
    <li><strong>Critical value:</strong> Lab result so abnormal it requires immediate provider notification.</li>
    <li><strong>SBAR:</strong> Situation, Background, Assessment, Recommendation — structured communication tool.</li>
    <li><strong>Levine technique:</strong> Method for wound culture collection using swab rotation over 1 cm² at wound base.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
